= Conversion Tools

These tools help you avoid the most common beginner mistake: confusing polite interest with real demand.

#block(inset: 8pt, radius: 4pt, stroke: 0.5pt, fill: rgb("FFFFFF"))[#strong[The 10-Message Test]
#v(3pt)
Send 10 direct, personal messages before judging an idea. Do not count likes, compliments, or vague interest. Count replies that show pain or willingness to act.

#strong[Your notes]
#v(3pt)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)

]

#block(inset: 8pt, radius: 4pt, stroke: 0.5pt, fill: rgb("FFFFFF"))[#strong[The \$10 Tiny Offer Test]
#v(3pt)
Turn your idea into one small thing someone could buy for around \$10. If nobody wants the tiny version, do not build the big version yet.

#strong[Your notes]
#v(3pt)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)

]

#block(inset: 8pt, radius: 4pt, stroke: 0.5pt, fill: rgb("FFFFFF"))[#strong[The Polite Interest Trap]
#v(3pt)
People saying 'cool idea' is not demand. Demand looks like questions, urgency, payment, referrals, or asking when it is available.

#strong[Your notes]
#v(3pt)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)
#line(length: 100%)

]

#block(inset: 8pt, radius: 4pt, stroke: 0.5pt, fill: rgb("FFFFFF"))[#strong[The Silence Rule]
#v(3pt)
If people ignore the offer after multiple direct asks, treat silence as data. Do not argue with the market.

